{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"964b1c7c-80a5-4e63-918c-7ba599ad31c4","content":"No repo content here, so this is a general guidance plan. Here's a step-by-step diagnostic and fix procedure:\n\n---\n\n## Diagnostic & Fix Plan: .NET MAUI Workloads + Android SDK\n\n### Phase 1 — Snapshot current state\n\n```powershell\n# Run all three; save output for comparison later\ndotnet --info\ndotnet workload list\ndotnet workload search maui\n```\n\nNote which SDK version is **active** (first line of `dotnet --info`) and which workloads show as installed. Mismatches between the SDK band (e.g. `8.0.300`) and the workload manifest band are the most common cause.\n\n### Phase 2 — Check for stale/conflicting SDKs\n\n```powershell\n# List every SDK on disk\ndotnet --list-sdks\n```\n\nIf you see **multiple feature bands** (e.g. `8.0.204` *and* `8.0.301`), workloads installed for the old band won't satisfy the new one. You can either:\n\n- Pin via `global.json` to the old SDK while you sort things out, **or**\n- Continue below to update workloads for the new band.\n\n### Phase 3 — Update workloads (safe when done correctly)\n\n`dotnet workload update` **is safe** — it updates manifests and packs to match your current SDK band. The key caveats:\n\n```powershell\n# Recommended: run in an elevated (Admin) terminal\ndotnet workload update --from-previous-sdk\n```\n\n`--from-previous-sdk` tells it to migrate workload selections from your old band so you don't lose anything. Without it, only workloads already registered to the *new* band are updated.\n\nIf that still leaves MAUI missing:\n\n```powershell\ndotnet workload install maui\n```\n\n### Phase 4 — Fix the Android SDK\n\nMAUI workloads bundle an Android SDK via `microsoft-net-sdk-android`. If builds still fail with Android SDK path or license errors:\n\n1. **Check the path VS / MAUI expects:**\n   ```powershell\n   # Typical default locations:\n   #   %LOCALAPPDATA%\\Android\\Sdk          (Android Studio)\n   #   %PROGRAMFILES(x86)%\\Android\\android-sdk  (VS installer)\n   ```\n2. **Set `ANDROID_HOME` explicitly** (if not set or pointing to the wrong copy):\n   ```powershell\n   [System.Environment]::SetEnvironmentVariable(\"ANDROID_HOME\",\n       \"$env:LOCALAPPDATA\\Android\\Sdk\", \"User\")\n   ```\n3. **Accept licenses** (the most common \"hidden\" failure):\n   ```powershell\n   & \"$env:ANDROID_HOME\\cmdline-tools\\latest\\bin\\sdkmanager.bat\" --licenses\n   ```\n4. **Verify required API level is installed.** Your `.csproj` declares a `<TargetFramework>` like `net8.0-android35.0`. The matching platform must exist:\n   ```powershell\n   & \"$env:ANDROID_HOME\\cmdline-tools\\latest\\bin\\sdkmanager.bat\" --list | Select-String \"platforms;android-\"\n   ```\n   Install if missing:\n   ```powershell\n   & \"$env:ANDROID_HOME\\cmdline-tools\\latest\\bin\\sdkmanager.bat\" \"platforms;android-35\"\n   ```\n\n### Phase 5 — Verify the fix\n\n```powershell\ndotnet workload list            # should show maui, android, etc.\ndotnet build YourApp.csproj -f net8.0-android   # (adjust TFM to match yours)\n```\n\n### Quick-reference decision tree\n\n| Symptom | Fix |\n|---|---|\n| `NETSDK1147: workload not installed` | `dotnet workload install maui` |\n| `Workload version mismatch` | `dotnet workload update --from-previous-sdk` |\n| `AndroidSdkDirectory not set` | Set `ANDROID_HOME` env var |\n| `License not accepted` | Run `sdkmanager --licenses` |\n| `Platform API XX not found` | Install via `sdkmanager \"platforms;android-XX\"` |\n\nRun Phase 1 → 5 in order and you should land in a consistent state. The `dotnet workload update` command your colleague suggested is the right call — just add `--from-previous-sdk` to carry forward your old workload selections.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"4a87b92a-9608-4ee1-ac4b-f3b7d5e37814","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The working directory is empty. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development on Windows 10 - there's no codebase to explore. I'll provide a diagnostic and fix plan based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI, workloads, and Android SDK management.","outputTokens":1157,"requestId":"77EE:19D0BE:7D547D0:8B9C123:69EABFE3"},"id":"da0503d2-1735-4e6d-a63b-8a7c1f42f3be","timestamp":"2026-04-24T00:57:32.855Z","parentId":"e477c89c-dfbf-42f3-8d58-4afd4d233e0b"}
